article.description: Carmelo Anthony hit a game-winning layup with six seconds left to lift the Nuggets to a 99-98 victory over the Sonics.
article.headline: 'Melo struggles, but Nuggets win
article.linkText: Miller nears triple-double as Nuggets beat Sonics
article.story: SEATTLE (AP) -- Carmelo Anthony made his first trip to Seattle a memorable one. The standout rookie scored 14 points, hitting a layup off an inbounds play with six seconds left that lifted the Denver Nuggets to a 99-98 victory over the Seattle SuperSonics on Wednesday night. "We run that play every day in practice," Anthony said. "It never works in practice." Anthony shot 6-for-18 with six rebounds and six assists, a performance that Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik characterized as "shaky" for a youngster learning to play in the NBA. "What's happening is that he's 19 years old and on the road," Bzdelik said. "He's got Rashard Lewis on him about 40 percent of the time, so a shaky game is all relative." It sure was an exciting finish, though. After a timeout with 14.1 seconds left, Seattle's Rashard Lewis drove on Nene and drew a foul just as he swished an 8-foot runner on the left baseline with 10.8 seconds to play. His three-point play gave the Sonics a 98-97 lead. "You would think that would guarantee a win, but that's how the NBA works," Seattle center Jerome James said. Bzdelik called timeout and set up a play for Anthony. He inbounded, then got the ball back near the top of the arc and drove for the winning layup, which rolled on the rim and dropped. "I saw the opening," Anthony said. "Everybody said, 'Don't lay it up. Dunk.' I always lay it up in practice. But it worked. I went to the hole real hard and it went in." Said Seattle coach Nate McMillan: "He did what guys do in that situation. He put his head down and made a tough shot over two defenders. I thought we played it pretty good. We just didn't get a break." The Sonics had a chance to win, but Marcus Camby blocked a shot at the top of the key by Antonio Daniels. "It's tough," Daniels said. "Going back with six seconds on the clock, you just try to get a shot up. You can't afford to pull it out and set something up because the clock is running." It was the second straight night Seattle lost on a last-second play, coming right after an overtime loss at Phoenix. Lewis and Ronald Murray each scored 19 points for Seattle. Daniels added 18 and Vladimir Radmanovic had 12. Denver (16-9) pulled within one victory of last season's win total and moved percentage points ahead of San Antonio atop the Midwest Division. "This team is totally different from last year," said Camby, who blocked seven shots. "We have veteran leadership through free agency. It's a better ballclub." Andre Miller barely missed a triple double, with 20 points, 11 rebounds and nine assists. Voshon Lenard scored 19, Camby added 15 points on 7-of-10 shooting and Nene scored 14. Seattle built a 91-86 lead midway through the fourth quarter but the Nuggets charged back behind Miller, who scored five points in a 9-2 burst that put Denver ahead 95-93 with 2:26 to play. Calvin Booth tied it with a dunk, but Camby matched it at the other end with 1:43 to go, setting up the close finish. The Nuggets broke into a celebration at midcourt, with players running from the bench. Camby threw the ball deep into the stands, which he said stemmed from frustration over the officiating. "I was on the referees out there," Camby said. "If I can say and do other things to those refs without getting a fine, I would." Game Notes: Seahawks receiver Koren Robinson watched from the second row, dressed in a Sonics retro jersey. Cody Pickett, who just completed his college career as Washington's quarterback, also was on hand. ... Miller started one night after missing most of the second half in Denver's win over New Orleans because of an overextended his left shoulder. ... Seattle fell to 4-4 in back-to-back sets, including 1-1 at home.
